When every industry went forward and shit like making furniture became factorized, it didn't completely kill off traditional woodworkers. The music industry tried that when fighting Napster because digital distribution was the future while all the senile boomers wanted to force people to buy CD's, and if it wasn't for Steve Jobs saving their asses with iTunes they would've went the way of the dodo.

Have AI art have it's dedicated web space and have traditional art have it's dedicated web space. It can coexist, but it has to be in their own little isolated spheres so that everyone is happy.

Ultimately the people that bitch and moan about AI art the most are people who don't know how it works and people who know damn well their art is so bad that a computer does a better job than them. Anonymous Fri 24 May 2024 15:51:56 No.66008794 Report

>>66008281
OP here. We agree on pretty much everything, actually. Separate spaces FTW, and I do believe prompting takes at least a little effort, just not the same type of talent as drawing by hand.

Although I don't like the comparison to the Industrial Revolution. Woodworking, and cobbling, and metallurgy all used to be mom-and-pop "sovl" things that got industrialized, since now most people just go to Home Depot and get Nike sneakers. It really did replace most of the demand. Nobody goes to the local cobbler for shoes anymore. And woodworkers are not what they used to be since most people just go to ikea because it's good enough. But that's not a bad thing, because the wood and metal that people use to build houses is something they need to live, and shoes prevent a myriad of injuries and blisters and pain.
That is to say, my house and shoes and tables shouldn't be someone's art project; they're just supposed to work.

Art, on the other hand, is a luxury. No one needs it, anyone can make it with a piece of paper and a pencil, and most people have access to a camera with which they can post the art to the internet.
Trad artists won't be completely removed, but a lot of them will be replaced because the AI product really is good enough for the average consumer, especially for such a low cost of production.
However art doesn't need to be good in the way my house needs to be good. Ifs less about quality, just needs to say "I really tried on this, wanted to make you think this waifur is cute." The bar is so much higher with AI, but it still exists which is why you have to respect the prompting craft but also separate it from traditional artwork.

Anonymous Fri 24 May 2024 16:13:10 No.66009168 Report
Quoted By: >>66009728
>>66008794
I agree, the Industrial Revolution comparison was a bad one because of that "necessity vs luxury" distinction. Art is something people do to express themselves, something that's way higher on the human needs pyramid than everything the Industrial Revolution (and it's consequences) have improved. Art is nothing but self-expression, people have created art and will continue to do so because they like it. Bass players won't ditch their hobby because a FM synth can do noises, they love all the funky ways they can slap the strings to make noise.

"AI art", or rather machine learning image generation, isn't as much a form of self-expression as it is an elaborate toy. It goes beyond prompt engineering, there are parameters that completely change the output, different models behaving differently with different parameters, and with ComfyUI now it adds a whole new array of control over the process like ControlNet nodes. Reading and understanding research papers is also a big thing, if you were to call it something, it's an art of mastery of the man over the machine as the diffusion models are opaque black boxes, and you have to figure out how to control them. Again, completely different from art with it's own share of hurdles and ways of the way you influence the final result. It's the biggest threat to the artists that do the "necessities" like advertisements, corporate slides and other inherently "souless" things like that. Then it's that it's own unique hobby that's opposite to regular art.

That's fair. Even though plagiarism was a thing since forever, I can understand why artists fear machine learning as it trivializes the entire process. But this moves the argument to the supply and demand part, what is the demand for machine learning copies of an artist's artstyle and what's the demand for this artist's work? Image gens can plagiarize, but they don't have to, they can mix existing styles, modify them, or have completely unique ones, and it's more likely that more people demand completely different generation styles than generation styles plagiarizing other artists. Then at the very end of it, the artist will have his imperfections in his work and he'll ultimately have the most creative control over the final product, as generated images will have their limitations due to the nature of the technology.

I believe artists shouldn't panic. They should learn about what ML image gen is, what is it's nature, and if they base their livelihood on drawing, they should think about what they can do, or already do differently to ML gens, and what people demand which product. Chances are they'll go by just well, because even image gen people like me don't feel okay with paying for gens plagiarizing someone else's work, and people who like the artist's work will want to support them, so their livelihoods will be secured. The demand for McDonald's isn't the same as demand for small business restaurants, and both exist and thrive, because different people have different demands. And the infinite supply of ML gens is meaningless when the demand for it is lower than for the low supply regular art.

Also, there are a lot of analogies to be made with video game piracy and DRM. If people can't pirate your game, they won't pay for it either, because they were never willing to do so, and in both cases you wouldn't earn that profit. If your product is in demand, and you offer great value, you will stay in business. Keep doing what you're doing.
